{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Operation certificates — asymmetric + environment-attributed + per-project required-environment\n\n## Context\nrebar's operation certificates (plan-review and completion-verifier verdicts) are today **local\nself-attestations**: signed with a per-clone **symmetric HMAC secret** and verified only by the\nsame clone (`foreign_key` if verified elsewhere — `src/rebar/signing.py`). Nothing at merge\n(Gerrit `Verified` / CI) re-verifies them, so they are local discipline, **not enforceable\ncontrols**, and no third party can verify one without the forge-capable secret. This epic migrates\noperation-certs to **asymmetric** signatures on the attestation foundation, **attributes** each to\nthe signing **environment** (verify-by-anyone against that environment's public key), and lets a\nproject **optionally require** a certificate from a specific trusted environment. **Beneficiary:**\nhigh-assurance projects that need a gate verdict they can trust was not forged by the developer who\nwanted to pass it — while low-security projects keep the fast local-report behavior. This epic\ndelivers the end state in which **both** signature types are asymmetric.\n\n> **Prerequisites shipped (drift note, 2026-07-13).** Both prerequisite epics have landed on `main`:\n> the **foundation** epic (`2fd4` / brilliant-curly-songbird) shipped the attestation substrate at\n> `src/rebar/attest/` (DSSE+PAE `dsse.py`, the source-pinned per-kind `POLICY` table in `registry.py`,\n> the SSHSIG scheme `sshsig.py`, and HMAC-as-legacy `hmac_legacy.py`); the **identity** epic\n> (`e68d` / gnu-whale-ichor) shipped an authenticated-authorship **merge-gate CI job**\n> (`.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml`, which walks the *merged log* and grandfathers via\n> `ENFORCE_SINCE`), an in-toto **merged-log ledger**, and **era-scoped commit-ancestry key validity**\n> (`src/rebar/attest/authorship.py`: validity as `(commit, intra_idx)` positions\n> `added_at_commit`/`revoked_at_commit`, compared with `git merge-base --is-ancestor`; verdict\n> `key_not_valid_at_era` is already in `src/rebar/schemas/verify_signature_result.schema.json`). This\n> epic was planned before those landed and originally described building the merge-gate, ledger, and\n> era-scoped rotation itself. It now **reuses** that shipped machinery rather than building parallel\n> copies — see the reuse notes inline below and the proposal comment on this epic.\n\n## Approach (and why)\n- **Environment-attributed, asymmetric op-certs.** Any environment signs with its own asymmetric\n  Ed25519 key via the foundation's substrate (namespace `rebar.opcert.v1`); the certificate\n  attributes to that environment and is verifiable by anyone against its public key. This matches\n  the existing per-environment model (a dev machine and a shared server are both \"environments\")\n  and restores the clean two-actor split (op-cert = **environment**; authorship = person, the\n  identity epic). The two kinds stay **orthogonal in actor and threat model** — different key,\n  trust-root, and namespace, so a signature is never valid across kinds — but the identity epic has\n  since **shipped**, so this epic now **reuses** its delivered machinery (the `verify-identity`\n  merge-gate CI job, the merged-log ledger, and the era-scoped commit-ancestry key-validity mechanism\n  in `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py`) rather than building parallel copies. \"Independent\" here means\n  the dependency is never inverted — op-certs are signed by environment keys, never by identity/person\n  keys — **not** that no code is shared.\n- **Per-project optional requirement.** A project pins trusted-environment public keys\n  **out-of-band** (a Gerrit-protected / CI config path, **never** the auto-pushed tickets branch)\n  and may require a specific environment's certificate for a gate. Low-security default: any/local\n  certificate is a **process record**, not a control. High-security: the **merge gate** (Gerrit/CI)\n  verifies the required environment's signature over the merged log. (Op-cert trust roots are\n  **out-of-band and high-authority** — deliberately unlike the identity epic's in-band TOFU authorship\n  keys; this distinction is preserved and is the reason op-cert cannot simply inherit identity's trust\n  model wholesale even while it reuses identity's era/merged-log plumbing.)\n- **Trusted remote execution for high assurance.** To obtain a required-environment certificate, a\n  developer routes the gate operation to a trusted `rebar-mcp` server (e.g. on AWS) that runs the\n  verifier and signs. **Integrity requirement (load-bearing):** that server MUST fetch the\n  authoritative state itself (ticket state from the tickets branch; code at the specific commit from\n  the review remote) and run the gate on THAT — never on client-provided inputs — or the signature\n  certifies a lie. This is a security/latency tradeoff the project opts into; the default local path\n  stays **offline and never wedges** a rebar operation.\n- **Verify against the pinned key, not the claimed key_id.** \"Require environment E\" verifies the\n  signature against E's out-of-band-pinned public key; the DSSE keyid is an unauthenticated hint.\n  Certificates bind `{ticket id, material fingerprint, merged-log position}` so they cannot be\n  replayed onto another ticket / stale state (the merged-log position is the `(commit, intra_idx)`\n  position model the substrate already uses). Environment-key rotation reuses the era-scoped\n  key-validity mechanism the identity epic shipped in `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` — validity as\n  commit-ancestry positions (`added_at_commit`/`revoked_at_commit`, compared with\n  `git merge-base --is-ancestor`), applied to the environment keyring — not a new wall-clock scheme.\n- **HMAC removal (contract phase).** Once op-certs verify asymmetrically, the legacy HMAC scheme\n  (`src/rebar/attest/hmac_legacy.py`, registered in the foundation's `attest/registry.py` `POLICY`\n  table) is removed — completing the migration begun in the foundation epic. Authorship already signs\n  asymmetrically (identity epic), so plan-review / completion-verifier op-certs are the last remaining\n  HMAC consumers.\n\nAlternative considered and rejected: **person-authority** op-certs signed by identity keys — it\ninverts the dependency on the identity epic and conflates the environment actor (who ran the gate)\nwith the person actor (who authored the event). Environment attribution keeps the epics independent\nand **composes** with authorship for full \"who ran + who closed\" attribution.\n\n## Scope\n- **In:** asymmetric environment-signed op-certs on the foundation's substrate; out-of-band\n  environment public-key trust config; per-project optional required-environment policy; merge-gate\n  verification (a CI job over the merged log, **extending the shipped `verify-identity.yaml` gate\n  pattern** rather than a fresh walker); the trusted `rebar-mcp` remote-execution path that\n  fetches authoritative state; certificate subject binding + era-scoped env-key rotation (**reusing\n  the identity epic's commit-ancestry validity machinery**); removal of the legacy HMAC scheme with an\n  expand-contract migration; IaC for the trusted MCP-server deployment (endpoint auth,\n  least-privilege IAM, KMS/secrets); docs + ADR.\n- **Out:** the signing substrate itself (foundation epic); person/authorship signing (identity\n  epic); the merge-gate walker / ledger / era-validity mechanism itself (identity epic — this epic\n  *reuses* it); transparency-log / keyless follow-ons.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- Operation certificates are asymmetric and verifiable by any third party against the signing\n  environment's public key; no shared secret is needed to verify.\n- A project can require a certificate from a specific trusted environment for a gate; the merge gate\n  enforces it over the merged log; without the requirement, local certificates remain a fast record.\n- The trusted environment's certificate reflects the authoritative state it fetched itself, not\n  client-provided inputs, so a developer cannot forge a passing verdict.\n- The legacy HMAC scheme is removed; both operation-cert and authorship signatures are asymmetric.\n- The default (low-security, local, offline) path never requires network and never wedges an op.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Operation certificates are produced/verified via the foundation's substrate with an Ed25519\n      environment key (namespace `rebar.opcert.v1`), registered as a new kind in the\n      `src/rebar/attest/registry.py` `POLICY` table alongside the foundation's HMAC-legacy and the\n      identity epic's `rebar.authorship.v1`; a test asserts a certificate signed by environment E\n      verifies against E's public key and fails against a different key.\n- [ ] A project config pins trusted-environment public keys from an out-of-band, review-gated path\n      (NOT the tickets branch); a test asserts a certificate from an environment not in the pinned\n      set fails the required-environment check, and that the check verifies against the pinned key,\n      not the certificate's self-claimed `key_id`.\n- [ ] A merge-gate CI job verifies the required-environment certificate over the merged log and\n      fails when a ticket that must carry one does not; it **extends the shipped `verify-identity.yaml`\n      merge-gate** (same merged-log walk + `ENFORCE_SINCE`-style grandfathering) rather than a\n      parallel job; a fixture demonstrates a missing/foreign certificate fails the job, and every\n      existing workflow trigger that should fire on the gate is classified INCLUDED/NO_FILTER.\n- [ ] Certificates bind `{ticket id, material fingerprint, merged-log position}`; a test asserts a\n      certificate cannot be replayed onto a different ticket or a mutated state. Environment-key\n      rotation uses era-scoped validity (valid-at-log-position, not wall-clock), **reusing the\n      commit-ancestry era mechanism and the `key_not_valid_at_era` verdict already in\n      `src/rebar/schemas/verify_signature_result.schema.json` (both shipped by the identity epic)**;\n      a test asserts a certificate from a key valid at its era verifies while one past its rotation\n      does not.\n- [ ] The trusted `rebar-mcp` remote path fetches ticket state and code-at-commit from authoritative\n      remotes itself and runs the gate on that; a test asserts a client-supplied doctored input does\n      NOT change the signed verdict. The AWS MCP-server infra declares human/admin authentication for\n      its endpoint, least-privilege IAM for the signing key + repo read, and stores the signing key\n      in a secrets manager / KMS.\n- [ ] The legacy HMAC scheme is removed; a test asserts no code path signs or accepts an HMAC\n      operation-cert, and existing HMAC certificates are handled by an expand-contract migration\n      (documented cutover window / re-issue), not a flag-day break. Rollback: the required-environment\n      policy is opt-in and defaults off; disabling it reverts to local behavior.\n- [ ] Docs + ADR: environment-attribution model, low/high-security postures, the\n      authoritative-state-fetch integrity requirement, out-of-band trust root, merge-gate\n      enforcement, and HMAC removal + migration.\n\n## Intended decomposition (children)\n1. Asymmetric environment-signed op-cert kind on the foundation's substrate (+ subject binding\n   + env-key era rotation, folded in from former task 5893) — a new `rebar.opcert.v1` kind in\n   `attest/registry.py`'s `POLICY` table.\n2. Out-of-band trusted-environment key config + required-environment policy + verify-against-pinned-key.\n3. Merge-gate verification CI job over the merged log (+ new-prohibition consumer scan, CI-trigger\n   audit) — **extend the shipped `verify-identity` gate; do not stand up a parallel merged-log walker.**\n4. Trusted `rebar-mcp` remote-execution path that fetches authoritative state + its AWS infra (endpoint auth, IAM, KMS).\n5. ~~Env-key era-scoped rotation~~ — **folded into child 1** (former task 5893, dropped as\n   superseded); reuses `attest/authorship.py`'s commit-ancestry validity for the environment keyring.\n6. HMAC removal (contract) + expand-contract migration of existing certificates.\n7. Docs + ADR.\n\n## Prior art / grounding\nDSSE (keyid is an unauthenticated hint — verify against pinned keys); OpenSSH `allowed_signers`\nvalidity intervals; git SSH-signing trust-file model; RFC 8725 (alg-confusion); key-transparency\nlineage (equivocation) noted as a later option. Depends on the foundation epic's substrate\n(`src/rebar/attest/`, shipped). Reuses the identity epic's shipped merge-gate\n(`.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml`), merged-log ledger, and commit-ancestry era-validity\n(`src/rebar/attest/authorship.py`)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783962725738625001,"uuid":"60a54713-bdfe-407d-8d48-6558b1b54ed4"}